'''Jeffrey Bub''' (born 1942) is a [[physicist]] and philosopher of physics, and [[Distinguished Professor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philosophy.umd.edu/people/bub|title=Jeffrey Bub. Distinguished University Professor|publisher=University of Maryland, Department of Philosophy|accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref> in the Department of Philosophy, the Joint Center for Quantum Information and Computer Science, and the Institute for Physical Science and Technology at the [[University of Maryland, College Park]].<ref>[http://carnap.umd.edu/philphysics/bub.html Jeffrey Bub], Faculty page, University of Maryland, College Park (downloaded February 23, 2012)</ref>
He obtained his bachelor's degree in pure mathematics and physics from the [[University of Cape Town]]. A scholarship allowed him to work at [[Birkbeck College]] with [[David Bohm]] who had profound intellectual influence on his work.<ref>J. Bub: ''Interpreting the Quantum World'', as cited by Kent A. Peacock: ''Bub and the barriers to quantum ontology'' ([http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/0269859022000013346 preview])</ref> Bub obtained his PhD in Mathematical Physics from [[London University]] in 1966. Before taking up his position as professor at the University of Maryland in 1986, he worked at the [[University of Minnesota]], [[Yale University]], [[Tel Aviv University]], and the [[University of Western Ontario]]. He has been visiting professor at [[Princeton University]], Yale University, the [[University of California at Irvine]], the CPNSS at the [[London School of Economics]], the [[University of California at San Diego]], the [[Perimeter Institute for Theoretical Physics]], and the Institute for Quantum Optics and Quantum Information at the [[University of Vienna]].<ref name="symposia-templeton-cv">[http://symposia.templeton.org/deep_beauty/bios.html#bub CV] at John Templeton Foundation (downloaded February 23, 2012)</ref>
His main research interests relate to quantum foundations, [[quantum information]], [[quantum computation]], and [[quantum cryptography]]. In 1998, his book ''Interpreting the Quantum World'' won the [[Lakatos Award]].<ref>[http://users.ox.ac.uk/~everett/biographies.htm#Jeffrey_Bub Short CV, Cambridge University] (downloaded February 23, 2012)</ref> In 2005 he received the University of Maryland's ''Kirwan Faculty Research and Scholarship Prize'' for his work in the area of quantum foundations and quantum information.
Bub has published over 100 scientific articles; the first of these are three articles authored together with David Bohm and published in 1966 and 1968.
==Publications== ;Books: *Jeffrey Bub: ''Interpreting the Quantum World'', Cambridge University Press, 1997,<ref name="symposia-templeton-cv"/> {{ISBN|978-0-521-65386-2}} (revised paperback edition, 1999) – [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/0269859022000013346 Review] by Kent A. Peacock *Jeffrey Bub: ''The Interpretation of Quantum Mechanics (The Western Ontario Series in Philosophy of Science)'', Springer, 1974, {{ISBN|978-90-277-0465-8}} *{{cite book| url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/11232.html| title=Totally Random |publisher= Princeton University Press| year=2018| isbn= 9780691176956 }}
